MEMORANDUM OF POINTS AND AUTHORITIES (SHORT FORM)
-------------------------------------------------

### A. Authority to Shorten Time

Under **CRC 3.1300(b)**, the Court may, on application supported by a declaration showing **good cause**, prescribe **shorter times** for filing and service of papers than those specified in **CCP § 1005**.   Section 1005(b) likewise authorizes the Court to **"prescribe a shorter time"** for hearing and briefing of motions.  

Because Plaintiff's Motion to Compel is already on calendar and supported by a separate moving and supporting papers, an **Order Shortening Time** is the appropriate procedural mechanism to ensure the Motion can be heard in a time frame that allows the requested relief to be meaningful.

### B. Ex Parte Standard and Narrow Relief Requested

The **ex parte rules (CRC 3.1200--3.1207)** govern this Application. They require written application, supporting declaration showing **irreparable harm or immediate danger**, a declaration regarding notice, and a proposed order. 

Here, Plaintiff seeks **only scheduling relief**---an advancement of the hearing date and a condensed briefing schedule---not an adjudication of the Motion's merits. This narrow relief is appropriate for ex parte treatment, provided that good cause and the requisite declarations are presented, which Plaintiff has done.

### C. Good Cause Shown in the Record and Supporting Declarations

Good cause exists where, as here:

-   A party **fails to appear** at a properly noticed deposition without seeking a protective order, justifying a motion to compel and sanctions under **CCP § 2025.450**;

-   **Discovery has closed**, and without post-cutoff leave under **CCP § 2024.050**, Plaintiff cannot complete essential party testimony; and

-   The court's calendar places the hearing **so late** that, absent an OST, Plaintiff's ability to use the deposition in **trial preparation and motion practice** will be materially impaired.

These facts, detailed in the **Declaration of Michael James Romero (Urgency)**, establish the **good cause and irreparable prejudice** required by **CRC 3.1202(c)** for ex parte scheduling relief while still allowing Defendant a fair opportunity to oppose the Motion on the merits.

The requested briefing schedule (Opposition 5 court days before hearing; Reply 2 court days before) tracks common practice for shortened-time motions and maintains due process protections for Defendant.

